  "stage": {
    "id": "course_core",
    "stageNumber": 2,
    "title": "Core: How Attention Works",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "scaled_dot_product_attention",
        "title": "Scaled Dot-Product Attention",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Queries match Keys\n- Values weighted by scores\n- Scaling prevents vanishing gradients\n\nThe attention formula Attention(Q,K,V) = softmax(QK^T/√d_k)V divides by √d_k to keep softmax gradients stable. Without scaling, large dot products squash gradients to near-zero.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "multi_head_attention",
        "title": "Multi-Head Attention: Seeing Multiple Perspectives",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- 8 parallel attention heads\n- Different representation subspaces\n- Attention from multiple viewpoints\n\nMulti-head attention runs 8 independent attention mechanisms in parallel, each learning to focus on different aspects (e.g., one head for grammar, another for semantics). Results are concatenated.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "encoder_decoder",
        "title": "Encoder-Decoder Architecture",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- 6 encoder layers\n- 6 decoder layers\n- Cross-attention between them\n\nThe encoder processes input and outputs representations. The decoder attends to these encoder outputs via cross-attention while generating output token-by-token, combining self-attention (to itself) with encoder context.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "positional_encoding",
        "title": "Positional Encoding: Adding Sequence Order",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Sinusoidal functions\n- No learned parameters\n- Encodes absolute position\n\nUnlike RNNs that process left-to-right, attention treats all positions equally. Sinusoidal positional encodings (sin/cos waves at different frequencies) inject position information before attention computes relationships.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "feedforward_networks",
        "title": "Position-wise Feed-Forward Networks",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Two-layer MLP per position\n- 512→2048→512 expansion\n- ReLU nonlinearity\n\nEach layer includes an MLP that expands attention outputs to 2048 dimensions (adding capacity), applies ReLU nonlinearity, then contracts back to 512. This adds expressivity beyond attention.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "self_attention",
        "title": "Self-Attention: Sequence Attends to Itself",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Positions attend to all other positions\n- Computes all relationships in parallel\n- Core of encoder\n\nSelf-attention computes how much each position should attend to every other position. For 10 tokens, all 10×10=100 pairwise relationships are computed in parallel, enabling the model to directly relate distant words.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-2",
      "question": "How many relationships does self-attention compute for a 10-token sequence? A) 10 B) 100 C) 1024",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "True",
        "False"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "100",
